I'm a documentary photographer and former Royal Marine Commando. I've covered everything from the war in Syria, Civil uprising against the government in Santiago, Chile, anti-poaching teams in Kenya and Zimbabwe, Israeli and Palestinian conflict over the west bank and gaza strip (from both sides of the coin) and numerous other projects, I've had awards from Olympus, The Nikon Foundation, The Royal Photographic Society, among others. I have picked up skills of intuition over the years, and the one thing I noticed about Extinction Rebellion was the diversity of people involved. When I covered them during the London, Berlin and New York protests (I had to get around the world a lot for that few weeks) including the build up to all of their protests (about 14 months prior to the big events themselves), there were warehouse workers, carers, scientists, former police officers, students, firemen, doctors, nurses, mechanics, kitchen stewards, three British soldiers who went AWOL to do this, there were taxi drivers who had quite because they were worried, entrepreneurs, web designers, factory workers, assemblers...there were all sorts of people, from all walks of life there. If you have kids, based on what I learnt from the environmental scientists (at Cambridge, Oxford, Warwick, Portsmouth, Southampton and York unis during my time working on this documentary photography project) then I would be seriously worried about what those children will have to look forward to, even in 15 - 20 years. I have kids, it certainly worried me.
